                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6831/239: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-07T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >December 7, 1939—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 7—1:17 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>268. My telegram No. 230, November 1, 4 p.m. The Minister of National Economy has
                    requested a postponement of further conversations until early in January on the
                    ground that the continuing chaotic condition of Greek foreign trade precludes
                    the present consideration of long term agreements. His attitude may be
                    understood partly in connection with the Allied blockade of German exports which
                    has caused the Greek authorities great alarm and is even occupying the attention
                    of the Foreign Office and the Premier.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
